00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:21.990
researching this book.

00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:28.040
So young scholars as Stuart
Little often called his students,

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:30.550
often ask me where ideas come from.

00:03:30.550 --> 00:03:33.490
And the idea for this book
came innocently enough.

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:38.190
I was walking my dogs as I do every
day and sometimes ideas come easy

00:03:38.190 --> 00:03:40.690
and sometimes you have
to go after them.

00:03:40.690 --> 00:03:43.620
This one just popped
into my head one day

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:46.060
as I was looking for
next my biography.

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:48.160
I wanted to do another biography.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:51.890
I had done a few and I love
the research part of it.

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:55.320
Life is always a rich and
steady time when you're waiting

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:58.640
for something to happen or
to hatch, E.B. White said.

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:00.320
And one of the things I discovered

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:04.560
in researching this biography was
how much E.B. White loved eggs.

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:05.860
Eggs of all kinds.

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:08.170
So the book begins
and opens with eggs.

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:12.810
He wrote a chicken primer and of
course, Charlotte lays the eggs

00:04:12.810 --> 00:04:15.460
in the doorway of the barn
which was the inspiration

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:18.060
of -- for Charlotte's Web.

00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:23.370
Immediately, questions came
up that had to be answered.

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:28.750
I wanted to know how did he come up
with the idea for Charlotte's Web?

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:32.160
How many drafts did it
take him to write the book?

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:35.360
And living in Maine, I
knew that he loved Maine.

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:38.660
How young was he when he
finally -- when he -- sorry.

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:40.690
First came to Maine?

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:45.460
And most importantly, what were
the names of all of his dogs?

00:04:45.460 --> 00:04:52.350
So some of the dogs -- some of his
dogs have the same name as my dogs.

00:04:52.350 --> 00:04:56.660
We were totally different
kinds of kids but there --

00:04:56.660 --> 00:04:58.810
we had a few things in common.

00:04:58.810 --> 00:05:00.550
When E.B. White was older,

00:05:00.550 --> 00:05:05.130
someone asked him what dime novels
he read when he was growing up?

00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:07.850
And he said, never
read a dime novel.

00:05:07.850 --> 00:05:11.460
I spent my youth on a
bicycle and in trees.

00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:12.760
We had that in common.

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:15.610
I spent my youth on
a bicycle with dogs.

00:05:15.610 --> 00:05:19.720 position:56%
I loved to go to the library but I
was not a particularly great reader.

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:23.070
Doesn't mean I didn't like books
but I didn't love reading as much

00:05:23.070 --> 00:05:27.900
as I did making art and playing
with these kids that you see.

00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:30.920
Who here had spirographs
and Etch-A-Sketches?

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:32.520
Yes me too.

00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:36.860
So paint by numbers and color
forms and all those things --

00:05:36.860 --> 00:05:40.570
these things that looks like
toys are really wonderful

00:05:40.570 --> 00:05:42.050
design teachers.

00:05:42.050 --> 00:05:43.610
So I was learning to make design.

00:05:43.610 --> 00:05:46.410
I was kind of preparing
myself to be an artist.

00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:49.110
Anybody here grow up in the
New York metropolitan area

00:05:49.110 --> 00:05:53.580
and have John Gnagy for -- a few
hands up there who taught us how

00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:56.640
to draw on Saturday mornings.

00:05:56.640 --> 00:05:59.160
And of course, I go to
my studio all the time.

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:00.960
More preparation.

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:03.270
The artist Teresita
Fernandez said that --

00:06:03.270 --> 00:06:07.740
says that making art is a
solitary process and it is.

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:11.800
So every day I go to my studio
just the way people go to work.

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:14.010
Kids go to school.

00:06:14.010 --> 00:06:16.240
I go to my studio.

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:21.050 position:56%
Early on in my career, I read that
Joyce Carol Oates said that she went

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:24.340
